  "prompt": "Why don't bikes have a gear indicator?",
  "response": "Actually, many modern motorcycles and some higher-end bicycles do have gear indicators. However, for many bicycles, there are several reasons why gear indicators are not standard:\n\n1. Simplicity: Most bicycles are designed to be simple and affordable.\n\n2. Cost: Adding a gear indicator would increase the bike's price.\n\n3. Mechanical vs. Electronic Shifting: Traditional mechanical gear systems make it difficult to electronically track gear position.\n\n4. Rider Awareness: Experienced cyclists typically develop an intuitive sense of their current gear through sound, pedaling effort, and muscle memory.\n\n5. Limited Complexity: Unlike motorcycles, bicycles have fewer gears and are generally simpler machines.\n\nSome high-end bicycles, particularly those with electronic shifting systems like Shimano Di2 or SRAM eTap, do offer gear indicators on display units or smartphone apps. Mountain bikes and road bikes with more advanced components are more likely to have this feature.\n\nFor most casual and recreational cyclists, the absence of a gear indicator isn't considered a significant drawback.",
